{{for|the process of immigrants adopting native culture|Cultural assimilation}} '''Nativization''' is the process whereby a [[language]] gains [[native speaker]]s.{{sfnp|Sankoff|Laberge|1972}} This happens necessarily where a [[second language]] used by adult parents becomes the [[native language]] of their children. Nativization has been of particular interest to [[linguists]], and to [[creolist]]s more specifically, where the second language concerned is a [[pidgin]].
Several explanations of [[Creole language|creole]] genesis have relied on prior nativization of a pidgin as a stage in achieving creoleness. This is true for [[Robert A. Hall, Jr.|Hall's]] (1966) notion of the pidgin-creole life cycle as well as [[Derek Bickerton|Bickerton]]'s [[The Language Bioprogram theory|language bioprogram theory]].{{sfnp|Hall|1966}}{{sfnp|Bickerton|1984}}
There are few undisputed examples of a creole arising from nativization of a pidgin by children.{{sfnp|Sankoff|Laberge|1972}}{{sfnp|Pfaff|1981}} The [[Tok Pisin]] language reported by {{Harvcoltxt|Sankoff|Laberge|1972}} is one example where such a conclusion could be reached by scientific observation.{{sfnp|Sankoff|Laberge|1972}} A counterexample is the case where children of [[Gastarbeiter]] parents speaking pidgin German acquired German seamlessly without creolization.{{sfnp|Pfaff|1981}} Broad treatments of [[creolization]] phenomena such as {{Harvcoltxt|Arends|Muysken|Smith|1995}} acknowledge now as a matter of standard that the pidgin-nativization scheme is only one of many explanations with possible theoretical validity.{{sfnp|Arends|Muysken|Smith|1995}}
